A. NOT gate
The NOT gate, also known as the inverter, takes a single binary input X , and generates its complement as the output Y . The circuit diagram of the NOT gate, composed of two transistors, is shown in Fig. 1(a). The N-type transistor is connected to a lower source voltage Vs = 0 on its left, while the P-type transistor is connected to a higher drain voltage Vd to its right. Both transistors are controlled by an input voltage Vin as in Eq. (2), which is treated as ﬁxed in a single gate, while the output voltage Vout is measured between the two transistors from the capacitor voltage Vg, which evolves according to Eq. (3). The kinetic diagram for our Markovian model is also shown in Fig. 1(a). Electrons can move ballistically between adjacent sites in the kinetic diagram according to a master equation, the details of which can be found in Appendix A [Eq. (A4)].
